# Command shasum

## What does this command do:

Print or check SHA checksums (SHA-1, SHA-224, SHA-256, SHA-384, SHA-512, SHA-512/224, SHA-512/256). Used to verify file integrity and detect tampering by comparing a known-good digest against a freshly computed one.

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: `sudo dnf install perl-Digest-SHA` (usually pre-installed with perl)
For Raspberry Pi install using: `sudo apt install libdigest-sha-perl` (usually pre-installed with perl)
For Mac install using: ships with macOS by default (provided by system Perl)

## Command path

For Fedora run: `/usr/bin/shasum`
For Raspberry Pi run: `/usr/bin/shasum`
For Mac run: `/usr/bin/shasum`

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://linux.die.net/man/1/shasum

## Command options

### Flags
    -a, --algorithm    1 (default), 224, 256, 384, 512, 512224, 512256
    -b, --binary       read in binary mode
    -c, --check        read SHA sums from the FILEs and check them
    -t, --text         read in text mode (default)
    -p, --portable     read in portable mode
                         (deprecated; use -U with -b for cross-platform)
    -U, --UNIVERSAL    read in Universal Newlines mode
                         produces same digest on Windows/Unix/Mac
    -0, --01           read in BITS mode
                         ASCII '0' interpreted as 0-bit,
                         ASCII '1' interpreted as 1-bit,
                         all other characters ignored
        --tag          create a BSD-style checksum
    -h, --help         display this help and exit
        --version      output version information and exit

### Check-mode flags (only with -c)
    --ignore-missing   don't fail or report status for missing files
    --quiet            don't print OK for each successfully verified file
    --status           don't output anything, status code shows success
    --strict           exit non-zero for improperly formatted checksum lines
    -w, --warn         warn about improperly formatted checksum lines

### Compute a checksum
# Default SHA-1 of a file
shasum file.iso

# SHA-256 (most common modern choice)
shasum -a 256 file.iso

# SHA-512
shasum -a 512 file.iso

# Checksum from stdin
echo -n "hello" | shasum -a 256

# Multiple files at once
shasum -a 256 *.tar.gz

# Read filenames from stdin (one per line)
find . -type f -name "*.txt" | shasum -a 256

### Save and verify checksums
# Write a checksum file
shasum -a 256 *.iso > SHA256SUMS

# Verify files against a checksum file
shasum -a 256 -c SHA256SUMS

# Verify silently, only show failures
shasum -a 256 -c --quiet SHA256SUMS

# Verify with no output, check exit code only
shasum -a 256 -c --status SHA256SUMS && echo "all good"

# Skip missing files (useful when checksum file lists more than you have)
shasum -a 256 -c --ignore-missing SHA256SUMS

# Strict mode: fail on malformed lines in the checksum file
shasum -a 256 -c --strict SHA256SUMS

### Compare against a published checksum
# Verify a single file matches an expected digest
echo "abc123...  file.iso" | shasum -a 256 -c

### Binary vs text vs universal
# Force binary mode (recommended for non-text files)
shasum -a 256 -b file.bin

# Universal newlines (cross-platform consistent digest for text)
shasum -a 256 -U -b file.txt

### BSD-style output
# Produces "SHA256 (file) = <digest>" instead of "<digest>  file"
shasum -a 256 --tag file.iso

### SHA-512/224 and SHA-512/256 truncated variants
shasum -a 512224 file
shasum -a 512256 file

### BITS mode (digest a stream of ASCII 0s and 1s)
echo -n "01100001" | shasum -0 -a 256

### Tamper detection workflow
# 1. Generate baseline manifest of a directory
find /etc -type f -print0 | xargs -0 shasum -a 256 > /var/backups/etc.sha256

# 2. Later, re-verify and look for changes
shasum -a 256 -c /var/backups/etc.sha256 | grep -v ': OK$'
